# Nikon Rant

I wanted to take some pictures off my mom's camera and was on my way to do the traditional method of plugging the SD card into my computer. Then I noticed the NFC symbol on the side of the camera. Figuring I could just get the images i needed via a quick NFC with my phone, I excitedly started tinkering with it to find out how. I ended up on a menu  on the camera that told me to tap the phone to the camera. Kinda strange since I didn't really select any photos to transfer yet, but i did it anyway. It took me to the Google Play Store page for a piece of proprietary Nikon software. Invasive, I thought, that they would want to be installed on my phone. I started regretting about my decision to try this method. I installed the app, and while sitting at a really long loading screen that just said "Getting Information, Please Wait", I started wondering if it would ask me to register for some service. Luckily, I was instead greeted by a screen asking me to turn on bluetooth. Bluetooth? I only wanted to NFC. But i kept down the rabbit hole, and complied. Next it told me to touch my phone to the camera again. Finally, some NFC going on for once, i thought. Upon doing so, the phone paired to the camera via bluetooth. I guess it was kinda like a shortcut, but with many more steps than the actual way to do it. I did the pairing, and was given the option to download photos, which i obviously selected. But it's not that easy of course! Y'know what radio in my phone WASN'T being used? Good old Wi-Fi! Nikon couldn't let me get away with that. The phone told me I needed to connect to the phone via wifi now. Unbelievable. I figured it would complete the ritual of invading my home by connecting to my home router, but I was wrong. The camera instead hosts its own AP, which my phone then connects to. I guess that's better than connecting to my home network, but i still felt like i had been violated at every turn. After all this, and only after all this, was I able to download the photos I wanted.
